      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of increased immigration argue that it boosts economic growth by injecting labor into shrinking domestic markets, driving innovation through diverse skill sets, and reducing the fiscal burden on public services by alleviating strain on welfare systems. Conversely, critics contend that unregulated influxes lead to wage suppression for native workers, strain on infrastructure and housing, and create security risks that undermine social cohesion and democratic stability.\n\nFrom an economic standpoint, the consensus leans toward viewing immigration as a net positive for long-term GDP and productivity, provided it is managed through targeted policies that ensure fair labor market integration and adequate social safety nets.",
