      "role": "user",
      "content": "so you're saying the risks are basically just \"temporary adjustments\" or \"distributional issues\"? that sounds like a way to brush off the actual impact on people's lives. if the \"risks\" are just people losing wages or not being able to afford housing, doesn't that make the negatives just as significant as the long-term GDP stuff? it feels like you're characterizing one side as structural reality and the other as just a minor hiccup.",
